00:23:50,027 --> 00:23:51,975
Again, he's a person.

544
00:23:51,985 --> 00:23:54,673
I'm gonna need you to try
a little harder, all right?

545
00:23:54,683 --> 00:23:57,024
Now, if I look away
for literally ten seconds

546
00:23:57,034 --> 00:23:59,765
he starts to die, and at some
point I'm gonna need to sleep

547
00:23:59,775 --> 00:24:03,257
or drop a deuce,
and I don't allow spectators.

548
00:24:04,157 --> 00:24:06,497
Yeah, there is some kind

549
00:24:06,507 --> 00:24:07,934
of bond happening there.

550
00:24:07,944 --> 00:24:09,152
Whoa.

551
00:24:09,162 --> 00:24:12,503
Your eye is crazy.

552
00:24:12,513 --> 00:24:14,288
Is that a wolf thing, or...

553
00:24:14,298 --> 00:24:15,855
Fairy thing.

554
00:24:15,865 --> 00:24:17,682
Can we focus on fish boy, please?

555
00:24:17,692 --> 00:24:19,597
It's not even attached to your head.

556
00:24:19,607 --> 00:24:21,556
You ever pop it out?

557
00:24:21,566 --> 00:24:24,385
Why the shit would I pop out
my own eyeball, Gordy?

558
00:24:24,395 --> 00:24:27,344
So you can point it

559
00:24:27,354 --> 00:24:28,693
at your gilled lover

560
00:24:28,703 --> 00:24:31,348
while you attend to...

561
00:24:31,400 --> 00:24:33,968
lady business.

562
00:24:38,713 --> 00:24:40,314
I don't know, man.

563
00:24:40,324 --> 00:24:42,882
It feels pretty stuck in there.

564
00:24:42,892 --> 00:24:45,459
Ah!

565
00:24:48,506 --> 00:24:50,672
Holy shit, it's working.

566
00:24:50,682 --> 00:24:52,369
I can still see out of it.

567
00:24:52,379 --> 00:24:55,469
You ever touch me again,
I'll pop out your balls.

568
00:24:57,645 --> 00:25:00,344
Uh...

569
00:25:02,520 --> 00:25:04,642
[LAUGHS] See?

570
00:25:04,652 --> 00:25:06,644
Problem solved.

571
00:25:06,654 --> 00:25:07,819
I don't know.

572
00:25:07,829 --> 00:25:10,518
This seems kind of problematic.

573
00:25:10,528 --> 00:25:13,226
Oh, I got just the thing.

574
00:25:17,535 --> 00:25:18,777
Really?

575
00:25:19,929 --> 00:25:24,227
Why does a veterinarian have
a pirate-themed eye patch?

576
00:25:24,237 --> 00:25:27,762
Maybe it's best we don't ask
a lot of follow-up questions.

577
00:25:30,374 --> 00:25:31,931
Jesus, what happened to you?

578
00:25:31,941 --> 00:25:33,758
Hey.

579
00:25:33,768 --> 00:25:35,021
[TENSE MUSIC]

580
00:25:35,031 --> 00:25:36,457
- Just...
- Hello, Alice.

581
00:25:36,467 --> 00:25:38,546
- Thought he was dead.
- Why'd you bring him here?

582
00:25:38,556 --> 00:25:41,288
Because I just might be
the only person alive

583
00:25:41,298 --> 00:25:42,942
who knows how to access the reservoir

584
00:25:42,952 --> 00:25:45,422
and save your friends.

585
00:25:45,432 --> 00:25:47,033
♪

586
00:25:47,043 --> 00:25:48,295
Mm.

587
00:25:48,305 --> 00:25:49,905
Okay, so the... the reservoir.

588
00:25:49,915 --> 00:25:52,342
Yes, well, that's what Martin called it.

589
00:25:52,352 --> 00:25:53,778
I thought it lacked

590
00:25:53,788 --> 00:25:56,259
a certain poetry.

591
00:25:56,269 --> 00:25:58,958
So I renamed it the Secret Sea.

592
00:25:58,968 --> 00:26:01,047
Right, the fourth...
the fourth "Fillory" book.

593
00:26:01,057 --> 00:26:02,077
Mm.

594
00:26:02,088 --> 00:26:04,655
Oh, I see you have a copy here.

595
00:26:05,426 --> 00:26:06,530
Ah.

596
00:26:06,540 --> 00:26:08,793
Oh, first edition.

597
00:26:08,803 --> 00:26:10,839
- That must be valuable.
- Yes.

598
00:26:10,849 --> 00:26:12,623
Well...

599
00:26:12,633 --> 00:26:14,495
even more so now.

600
00:26:14,505 --> 00:26:16,681
[CHUCKLES]

601
00:26:18,944 --> 00:26:20,544
The Watcherwoman in the books,

602
00:26:20,554 --> 00:26:23,236
she was...

603
00:26:23,247 --> 00:26:25,213
trying to steal all of magic
for herself, right?

604
00:26:25,224 --> 00:26:26,724
And then... and then Martin stops her.

605
00:26:26,734 --> 00:26:29,684
Most of that book is pure tosh.

606
00:26:29,694 --> 00:26:32,687
I had to invent that plot
from the whole class.

607
00:26:32,697 --> 00:26:36,647
It's... well, I couldn't exactly
publish the stories

608
00:26:36,657 --> 00:26:38,649
as the children
told them to me, could I?

609
00:26:38,659 --> 00:26:40,086
I mean, the "Flying Forest,"

610
00:26:40,096 --> 00:26:44,307
where the Chatwins discovered
recreational drug use?

611
00:26:44,317 --> 00:26:48,007
Poor little Jane hearing about
the birds and the bees from a...

612
00:26:48,017 --> 00:26:51,749
did you know that centaurs
view necrophilia

613
00:26:51,759 --> 00:26:53,969
as a way of honoring the dead?

614
00:26:53,979 --> 00:26:55,884
Don't think I'd get a Carnegie Medal

615
00:26:55,894 --> 00:26:57,842
for explaining that to children.

616
00:26:57,852 --> 00:26:59,757
I mean, then there's all the...

617
00:26:59,767 --> 00:27:02,021
all the exaggerations and the lies.

618
00:27:02,031 --> 00:27:05,676
I mean, Martin slaying
a dozen mercenaries,

619
00:27:05,686 --> 00:27:08,592
and Jane riding on top of a horse,

620
00:27:08,602 --> 00:27:10,638
what, 100 feet tall?

621
00:27:10,648 --> 00:27:12,118
I mean, what did she call it?

622
00:27:12,128 --> 00:27:14,511
- Cozy Horse.
- "Cozy Horse."

623
00:27:14,521 --> 00:27:16,861
Utter nonsense thrown in there

624
00:27:16,871 --> 00:27:19,125
just to see how much
they'd get me to believe,

625
00:27:19,135 --> 00:27:21,127
and then Jane insisted I keep it.

626
00:27:21,137 --> 00:27:24,652
In real life, the ending was...
was much darker.

627
00:27:24,662 --> 00:27:27,611
Oh, Martin did stop
the Watcherwoman, that's true.

628
00:27:27,621 --> 00:27:30,092
The Secret Sea was built

629
00:27:30,102 --> 00:27:32,051
by the 13th king of Fillory

630
00:27:32,061 --> 00:27:34,531
to consolidate power for himself.

631
00:27:34,541 --> 00:27:37,839
Martin wanted to make sure
that no one ever tried

632
00:27:37,849 --> 00:27:41,625
to do the same thing again
so he drained the Secret Sea,

633
00:27:41,635 --> 00:27:44,628
using the last few drops to set a trap

634
00:27:44,638 --> 00:27:47,588
for anyone who might
one day try to refill it.

635
00:27:47,598 --> 00:27:49,503
A... a curse.

636
00:27:49,513 --> 00:27:51,896
Right, so now one
of our friends is a fish.

637
00:27:51,906 --> 00:27:54,856
[LAUGHS] Well, he was 13 at the time.

638
00:27:54,866 --> 00:27:56,423
You have to forgive

639
00:27:56,433 --> 00:27:58,903
his rather adolescent sense of humor.

640
00:27:58,913 --> 00:28:00,949
- You know how to fix it?
- Mm-hmm.

641
00:28:00,959 --> 00:28:03,778
There's a garden
just outside the reservoir.

642
00:28:03,788 --> 00:28:06,607
The Drowned Garden, Martin called it.

643
00:28:06,617 --> 00:28:08,957
Never did know why.

644
00:28:08,967 --> 00:28:11,742
It reacts to your emotions.

645
00:28:11,752 --> 00:28:14,441
If you're happy, a flower blooms.

646
00:28:14,451 --> 00:28:16,921
If you're sad, another one.

647
00:28:16,931 --> 00:28:19,185
So one of the plants is the antidote?

648
00:28:19,195 --> 00:28:21,458
Indeed.

649
00:28:22,459 --> 00:28:24,712
To make it bloom...

650
00:28:24,722 --> 00:28:27,812
you have to truly love Fillory.

651
00:28:33,513 --> 00:28:36,724
Maybe when I was 12, but...

652
00:28:36,734 --> 00:28:38,769
I don't know, Fillory's taken away

653
00:28:38,779 --> 00:28:40,119
a lot of the shit I love.

654
00:28:40,129 --> 00:28:43,034
Martin had the same problem.

655
00:28:43,044 --> 00:28:45,602
He returned as an adult and...

656
00:28:45,612 --> 00:28:48,692
could not make the flower bloom.

657
00:28:48,702 --> 00:28:51,652
His innocent love for Fillory

658
00:28:51,662 --> 00:28:54,481
had... had soured.

659
00:28:54,491 --> 00:28:56,439
Think we can all say why.

660
00:28:56,449 --> 00:28:58,886
Quentin.

661
00:29:00,061 --> 00:29:03,054
It has to be you.

662
00:29:03,064 --> 00:29:05,796
I'm familiar with your books.

663
00:29:05,806 --> 00:29:09,148
Even considering
your recent experiences,

664
00:29:09,158 --> 00:29:12,151
Quentin has the best chance of...

665
00:29:12,161 --> 00:29:15,632
making the garden grow.

666
00:29:15,642 --> 00:29:17,939
[SIGHS]

667
00:29:17,949 --> 00:29:20,550
[COUGHING] We don't have much time.

668
00:29:20,560 --> 00:29:22,900
There's a contractor the Library uses

669
00:29:22,910 --> 00:29:24,119
who might be willing to...

670
00:29:24,129 --> 00:29:27,132
Text me if you find somebody. [COUGHING]

671
00:29:35,749 --> 00:29:37,785
So it's true? The Library has a cure?

672
00:29:37,795 --> 00:29:40,788
[SIGHS] I know, it's bullshit.

673
00:29:40,798 --> 00:29:43,192
Go with her before it's too late.

674
00:29:44,802 --> 00:29:46,750
If this is some noble shit

675
00:29:46,760 --> 00:29:49,676
about you not owing
the Library anything...

676
00:29:52,984 --> 00:29:54,018
Oh.

677
00:29:54,028 --> 00:29:55,672
You don't want to be cured.

678
00:29:55,682 --> 00:29:57,534
[SNIFFS]

679
00:29:57,545 --> 00:29:58,980
'Cause for all of the terrible shit

680
00:29:58,990 --> 00:30:00,764
we've been through, at least the upside

681
00:30:00,774 --> 00:30:03,027
is that you know that
there's a life after death

682
00:30:03,037 --> 00:30:06,161
and you get to spend forever
with the other Penny.

683
00:30:06,171 --> 00:30:07,858
And what part of that sounds bad?

684
00:30:07,868 --> 00:30:10,121
The part where you're dead.

685
00:30:10,131 --> 00:30:11,862
[SCOFFS]

686
00:30:11,872 --> 00:30:13,603
I may not know you the way he did,

687
00:30:13,613 --> 00:30:16,703
but I know that that would be
a hell of a waste.

688
00:30:18,096 --> 00:30:20,697
Yeah.

689
00:30:20,707 --> 00:30:22,883
Well, most things are.

690
00:30:27,975 --> 00:30:30,316
A lot's changed since I've been gone.

691
00:30:30,326 --> 00:30:31,752
Yes.

692
00:30:31,762 --> 00:30:34,711
The humans made lots of good stuff.

693
00:30:34,721 --> 00:30:36,060
[TENSE MUSIC]

694
00:30:36,070 --> 00:30:38,324
They spend their small lives
building things

695
00:30:38,334 --> 00:30:41,283
that we could smash in a heartbeat.

696
00:30:41,293 --> 00:30:42,371
Sounds fun.

697
00:30:42,381 --> 00:30:44,895
Perhaps you can tell me... [SIGHS]

698
00:30:44,905 --> 00:30:47,855
Do I have a name?

699
00:30:47,865 --> 00:30:51,337
Why would you need one?

700
00:30:51,347 --> 00:30:53,904
Starbucks, mostly.

701
00:30:53,914 --> 00:30:56,255
This whole time I felt so sorry for you.

702
00:30:56,265 --> 00:30:58,082
Lost and alone.

703
00:30:58,092 --> 00:31:00,346
But you weren't alone.
You were with the humans.

704
00:31:00,356 --> 00:31:03,218
You talk like them, you think like them.

705
00:31:03,228 --> 00:31:05,089
♪

706
00:31:05,099 --> 00:31:06,917
I ate a few of them.

707
00:31:06,927 --> 00:31:09,746
Yes, but you care about them.

708
00:31:09,756 --> 00:31:14,098
♪

709
00:31:14,108 --> 00:31:16,275
[SIGHS]

710
00:31:16,285 --> 00:31:17,885
♪

711
00:31:17,895 --> 00:31:19,103
You think I'm disappointed.

712
00:31:19,113 --> 00:31:21,628
I'm not.

713
00:31:21,638 --> 00:31:24,370
♪

714
00:31:24,380 --> 00:31:27,024
Are you scared of me, little brother?

715
00:31:27,034 --> 00:31:29,113
Would I have worked so hard
to bring you back

716
00:31:29,123 --> 00:31:31,725
if I was scared of you?

717
00:31:31,735 --> 00:31:35,206
All I thought about was you.

718
00:31:35,216 --> 00:31:38,035
After I remembered you existed, anyway.

719
00:31:38,045 --> 00:31:40,951
And all I thought about was revenge.

720
00:31:40,961 --> 00:31:44,215
And I got it for you already.

721
00:31:44,225 --> 00:31:46,653
I killed Bacchus.

722
00:31:46,663 --> 00:31:48,742
Iris.

723
00:31:48,752 --> 00:31:50,831
All of them.

724
00:31:50,841 --> 00:31:52,887
Everyone who hurt you.

725
00:31:53,800 --> 00:31:56,619
The question is, who put us here?

726
00:31:56,629 --> 00:31:59,970
♪

727
00:31:59,980 --> 00:32:01,320
Our parents.

728
00:32:01,330 --> 00:32:03,800
They made us, called us mistakes.

729
00:32:03,810 --> 00:32:05,149
Abandoned us.

730
00:32:05,159 --> 00:32:08,239
So, what do we do?

731
00:32:08,249 --> 00:32:10,677
I like murder as much as anyone,

732
00:32:10,687 --> 00:32:13,027
but I did all of this

733
00:32:13,037 --> 00:32:15,246
just to be with you.

734
00:32:15,256 --> 00:32:18,859
Can't we enjoy it
just for a little while?

735
00:32:18,869 --> 00:32:20,382
♪

736
00:32:20,392 --> 00:32:22,428
That's not what we were made for.

737
00:32:22,438 --> 00:32:26,823
It's not that I am terrified
of the Old Gods in any way.

738
00:32:26,833 --> 00:32:29,217
It's just, how do you kill

739
00:32:29,227 --> 00:32:32,002
an intangible thought creature?

740
00:32:32,012 --> 00:32:35,092
Where do you even stab?

741
00:32:35,102 --> 00:32:37,834
They're more vulnerable
than you think...

742
00:32:37,844 --> 00:32:40,010
if we can get to their realm.

743
00:32:40,020 --> 00:32:42,186
Which we cannot.

744
00:32:42,196 --> 00:32:45,668
We had a key. A scroll.

745
00:32:45,678 --> 00:32:48,192
Found it a very long time ago
on this world.

746
00:32:48,202 --> 00:32:49,455
The Order took it from us.

747
00:32:49,465 --> 00:32:51,718
They didn't even know what they had.

748
00:32:51,728 --> 00:32:53,110
Now...

749
00:32:53,120 --> 00:32:56,113
where would a bunch of librarians keep

750
00:32:56,123 --> 00:33:00,301
a very, very important scroll?

751
00:33:11,617 --> 00:33:12,826
Oh.

752
00:33:12,836 --> 00:33:14,131
Here.

753
00:33:14,141 --> 00:33:15,655
This has to be it.

754
00:33:15,665 --> 00:33:18,919
It's exactly as Martin described it.

755
00:33:18,929 --> 00:33:21,878
[STAMMERING]
Think... think happy thoughts

756
00:33:21,888 --> 00:33:23,793
about Fillory.

757
00:33:23,803 --> 00:33:25,534
Pure.

758
00:33:25,544 --> 00:33:28,363
Innocent.

759
00:33:28,373 --> 00:33:30,060
Maybe try talking to it.

760
00:33:30,070 --> 00:33:33,378
Okay, you just...

761
00:33:36,860 --> 00:33:39,592
Well...

762
00:33:39,602 --> 00:33:42,812
um, Fillory is...

763
00:33:42,822 --> 00:33:44,858
obviously great.

764
00:33:44,868 --> 00:33:47,991
Um, you know, talking bears, right?

765
00:33:48,001 --> 00:33:49,950
Who... who could hate that?

766
00:33:49,960 --> 00:33:53,867
And... and opium in the air.

767
00:33:53,877 --> 00:33:55,825
That was...

768
00:33:55,835 --> 00:33:57,697
smart.

769
00:33:57,707 --> 00:34:00,134
And...

770
00:34:00,144 --> 00:34:02,789
socialized centaur medicine.

771
00:34:02,799 --> 00:34:04,094
Are we screwed

772
00:34:04,104 --> 00:34:05,835
because Quentin can't
get it up for Fillory?

773
00:34:05,845 --> 00:34:07,794
- Just...
- Look, why don't you try...

774
00:34:07,804 --> 00:34:10,519
Okay, no, stop. I can't... look,
you're the one that ruined this.

775
00:34:10,530 --> 00:34:14,549
I can't do it with you over my
shoulder, so just... please, just go.

776
00:34:17,596 --> 00:34:19,903
God damn it.

777
00:34:22,209 --> 00:34:24,908
[SIGHS]

778
00:34:27,606 --> 00:34:29,859
Okay, um...

779
00:34:29,869 --> 00:34:32,427
when I was a kid
I... I loved the Fizzy River

780
00:34:32,437 --> 00:34:34,429
that they found in book two.

781
00:34:34,439 --> 00:34:36,605
And I loved...

782
00:34:36,615 --> 00:34:38,651
I loved the Upside-Down Desert.

783
00:34:38,661 --> 00:34:40,653
You know, the... [STAMMERING]

784
00:34:40,663 --> 00:34:43,960
I can't really picture it,
but, you know, it sounds...

785
00:34:43,970 --> 00:34:46,669
it sounds cool.

786
00:34:49,628 --> 00:34:51,185
I don't know, I can't... I'm sorry.

787
00:34:51,195 --> 00:34:54,546
- I just... I can't...
- Hey. Hey.

788
00:34:56,026 --> 00:34:58,105
I used to love Fillory when I was a kid

789
00:34:58,115 --> 00:35:01,586
because I didn't know what it was.

790
00:35:01,596 --> 00:35:03,588
Plover left out
all of the terrible shit,

791
00:35:03,598 --> 00:35:05,678
and most of the good stuff
he just made up.

792
00:35:05,688 --> 00:35:08,985
Even the fucking Cozy Horse is a lie.

793
00:35:08,995 --> 00:35:10,465
Remember what you told me

794
00:35:10,475 --> 00:35:12,467
about letting go of who you used to be?

795
00:35:12,477 --> 00:35:14,556
I know, I'm trying.

796
00:35:14,566 --> 00:35:16,950
Don't.

797
00:35:16,960 --> 00:35:19,779
I don't want you to.

798
00:35:19,789 --> 00:35:22,651
Believing in something...
really believing...

799
00:35:22,661 --> 00:35:24,958
is almost impossible.

800
00:35:24,968 --> 00:35:26,786
[BITTERSWEET MUSIC]

801
00:35:26,796 --> 00:35:29,658
But the Quentin I first met...

802
00:35:29,668 --> 00:35:32,487
he believed in magic.

803
00:35:32,497 --> 00:35:34,794
And in Fillory.

804
00:35:34,804 --> 00:35:36,970
He changed.

805
00:35:36,980 --> 00:35:39,886
He grew up.

806
00:35:39,896 --> 00:35:42,976
Being an adult doesn't mean
that you have to throw away

807
00:35:42,986 --> 00:35:45,630
what you used to love.

808
00:35:45,640 --> 00:35:48,503
Then what does it mean?

809
00:35:48,513 --> 00:35:51,680
Seeing the world through new eyes.

810
00:35:51,690 --> 00:35:56,511
♪

811
00:35:56,521 --> 00:35:59,296
And for what it's worth,

812
00:35:59,306 --> 00:36:01,037
